<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n05152k"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05152k">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05152k"> 152(k)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> darky</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Not to be confused with the obstinacy of official persons and others which is often displayed in verbal intransigence: as in the <mark>darky</mark> anecdote which C. S. Peirce was wont to relate.&mdash;&ldquo;You know, Massa, that General Washington and General Jackson was great friends, dey was. Well, one day General Washington he said to General Jackson, &lsquo;General, how tall should you think this horse of mine was?&rsquo; &lsquo;I don&apos;t know, General,&rsquo; says General Jackson. &lsquo;How tall is he, General Washington?&rsquo; &lsquo;Why,&rsquo; says General Washington, &lsquo;he is sixteen feet high.&rsquo; &lsquo;Feet, General Washington?&rsquo; says General Jackson, &lsquo;feet, General Washington? You mean hands, General.&rsquo; &lsquo;Did I say feet, General Jackson?&rsquo; said General Washington. &lsquo;Do you mean to say that I said that my horse was sixteen feet high? Very well, then, Gen&apos;ral Jackson, if I <i>said</i> feet, <i>if</i> I said feet, then I sticks to it.&rsquo; <small> C.K. Ogden and I.A. Richards <a name="OMOM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#OMOM"><cite title="source">The Meaning of Meaning</cite></a> (London: Kegan Paul, 1923) 346n</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
